title: For Sale:   Remington Model 8, 1917 Vintage, in .30 Remington, Original Pistol Grip Stock. Not an 81
postcontent: 50 ROUNDS of ORIGINAL Remington Ammo is available for an additional $100! Boxes are tattered, but ammo is in good shape! This is a very nice rifle, that has not been cut or drilled!  Shoots and Functions Excellent! In .30 Remington, NOT .30-30 - there was no listing for .30 Remington in the selections. The cartridge is like a rimless .30-30 though. Bore is good and it miked out right on .308, for you bullet casters. I got it some time ago with a broken firing pin - and I don't think it had been shot for 40 or so years. I disassembled, cleaned and oiled, installed a new firing pin, reassembled, and went out and shot most of a box of newly loaded cartridges (new brass) with 150gr. jacketed bullets, and adjusted the factory sights. My eyes aren't so great, but it did a pretty nice group at 50 yards (see pictures). It has quite a bit of original blue left for a 1917 vintage, and there are no extra holes from oddball sights or scope mounts anywhere on the rifle. The barrel shroud is not dented. The stock has been refinished, but it doesn't appear to have been overly sanded. There is one spot near the wrist where a piece apparently broke off when disassembled (probably the guy who broke the firing pin), and it was glued back on - not invisible, but it is very strong. There is a very small piece missing off of the tip of the wood forearm - grain orientation made that tiny piece weak. It never bothered me, and isn't very noticeable. It has a real nice crescent butt.  Apparently when the original firing pin was broken umpteen years ago, the owner at that time decided to try and punch out the safety, which resulted in a few dings on and around that pin.  It's not bad, but if you are looking for it, you will see it.  NOTE: THE RECEIVER HAS NOT BEEN DRILLED!!! It is still intact!   I'm allowed only 3 pictures - if you would like more, please feel free to ask. Really, it's in pretty nice shape for a 1917 vintage rifle. * * * * * * * * * * * * * * I had to relist this ad, due to some idiot flagging my ad as a scam - it surely isn't - I have the rifle, and invite you to stop by and inspect it face to face, and also pay cash for it on the spot. I'm located in WI, about 30 miles straight South of Madison. If you would like to hunt with an easy-shooting, antique autoloading rifle in nice condition and with good ballistics, this would be a good choice. Ballistics are about the same as an AR-style .308 out of a short (16") barrel (or a .30-30), with a lot less pressure! I reload new brass using .30-30 dies and a .30 Remington shell holder(same as .40 s&w!). I use W748 powder, and my last loads were 150 gr. Speer Hot-Cor bullets. Inspection of the cases showed the shoulders on the fired rounds being the same as my unfired cases. I intend to neck size only the once fired cases, and I chamber all of my hand loads to check for proper sizing. If you don't have any brass, I do have some (up to 40) that I might let go for an additional price. Remington still makes them once in a while though. Remember! 50 rounds of original factory ammo is available with the rifle! Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  H&R 22 Special-Top Break 9 shot in 22 LR-With unique 22 WRF frame
postcontent:
Classic 22 LR Revolver from H&R in great shape. Purchased from an Estate auction of a Firearms collector who had a note in the box stating this was a "One-of-collectible" as the barrel assembly is stamped  22 WRF CTG (WINCHESTER RIM FIRE CARTDRIGE) the predecessor to the 22 Mag., same bullet diameter (22) but the WRF was shorter than the 22 Mag. 
Apparently this pistol made it passed a sleepy inspector as the 9 shot cylinder is for a 22LR., frame & Calendar are matching #'s.  There is some holster wear on the bluing in a few areas but pistol is rust free and the cylinder locks up tight. Inside barrels lans/grooves are factory fresh with no corrosion. Fires in both single and double action. I taught my son & daughter to safely shoot with this piece and they love the break-top action as it make loading/unloading fun and easy! Very accurate pistol once you get used to the petite rear sights these came with.
More pictures upon request, have a look as pictures do speak a 1000 words.
Pistol has a 6" barrel with the gold front sight blade.

Selling for $300 OBO to Oregon residents 21 & over willing to sign a Bill of Sale.
Possible partial trades of factory .308 match or FMJ/BT ammo or some sterling SMG magazines, plus or minus cash on either end, but cash is king for this deal as I have some care repair needs.
I will advertise locally for this week, but after that, if not sold I will be auctioning on gunbroker.com where it will sell for more than my locally sold asking price, but after fees and the need/time to ship, it makes better sense to sell to an Oregon neighbor.
I would also be willing ship to an FFL for a fee, but then comes the trust issue on the buyers end that is hard to work around.
I will meet buyer at the Albertson parking lot off of SW Cornelius Pass Rd & SW Baseline Rd. on the Hillsboro/Beaverton border.
Lastly, for anti-spam purpose, any potential buyers or someone needing more information, please send your name & phone # so I know you are a legit Oregonian (not that there aren't Oregon spammers, but they are too busy in the sun and will be back in September! ;)

title: For Sale:  M1917 Eddystone WWI Era Battle Rifle $555
postcontent:
For sale is a M1917 Eddystone 30-06

Here is a nice M1917 Eddystone Enfield rifle. This rifle was extensively used during WW1 (more so than the 1903 Springfield), and limited use during WWII. The stock is well marked! The action on this rifle is crisp and smooth. I have fired the weapon, and it shoots quite well! The bore is very very good. Nice wood, no cracks.

The good:

H-S: High Standard WWII replacement barrel.

Barrel condition is mint, Muzzle Erosion just barely over 1

Shoots a nice tight grouping.

Excellent cartouches, one is “3 GM-K”

This cartouche was stamped by General Motors during WW2 as a rebuild or inspection mark. GM was one of a few contractors given a contract to inspect & rebuild the Springfield 1903 and 45,000 of the 1917's. This is not a common cartouche, they're primarily found on Remington 1917's

Rifle is fully functional and a great shooter!

title: For Sale:  Beware of Perth mint gold bar, not accusing just cautious read attached article
location: Mt pleas, north chuck, summerv, Charleston, South Carolina
postcontent:
First, I am not accusing the person with the 1 oz gold bar of anything.  He said it came from a family member so if it is real great, but if it is one of the numerous fake ones he may not know.

Being that gold is going for ver $1200 per ounce today if it's real it's a deal.

A while back the market was flooded with fake Perth bars.  Read the article attached to make sure it's legit before trading a firearm.

If the Front of the assay card says Certicard security Case and the Bar number on the back DOES NOT START with a B then it is fake.

http://www.chards.co.uk/news/perth-mint-fake-bars/
